"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 2 Chronicles chapters 13–17
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-2chronicles-13-17.py

Ch 13: Abijah's covenant-of-salt speech — the irrevocable Davidic covenant as type of Christ's
       eternal kingship; Jeroboam's golden-calf opposition types rejection of God's anointed.
Ch 14: Asa's prayer of sole reliance on YHWH — the paradigm of faith against overwhelming odds;
       dāraš (seek) as the theological diagnostic pointing toward Christ.
Ch 15: Azariah's "seek and you will find" (v2) directly anticipates Matt 7:7; covenant renewal
       with "all heart and soul" anticipates the new covenant's heart-inscription.
Ch 16: Asa's failure — reliance on Syria instead of YHWH; v9 "eyes of the LORD ranging" →
       Rev 5:6 (seven eyes of the Lamb); the negative exemplar of faith.
Ch 17: Jehoshaphat's Torah-mission throughout Judah — the sēper tôrat YHWH sent to every town
       anticipates the Great Commission; the Davidic model of seeking God.

Key decisions:
- "Covenant of salt" (13:5): classified as type — the permanent Davidic covenant fulfilled in Christ
- 15:2 "seek and you will find": allusion-level — not verbal quote but structurally parallel to Matt 7:7
- 16:9 "eyes of the LORD": theme pointing to Rev 5:6's seven eyes of the Lamb
- dāraš throughout: consistently named as the seeking-theology fulfilled in Christ as the one sought
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON2 = {
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>Abijah&rsquo;s accession &ldquo;in the eighteenth year of Jeroboam&rsquo;s reign&rdquo; situates the Davidic dynasty in direct temporal conflict with the northern rival. The Chronicler frames this as a contest between two claims on Israel&rsquo;s future: the Davidic covenant (which culminates in Christ) versus the usurping line of Jeroboam. Every generation of the Davidic dynasty is, in the Chronicler&rsquo;s reading, part of the unbroken chain leading to the one Son of David whose throne will be established forever (2 Sam 7:12-16; Luke 1:32-33).</p>",
    "2": "<p>War between Abijah and Jeroboam frames the entirety of this chapter as a conflict not merely political but theological: the kingdom held by David&rsquo;s descendants against the rebel dynasty. As a shadow, this Davidic-versus-rebel conflict anticipates the cosmic conflict between Christ, the final Davidic heir, and every power that opposes his reign &mdash; a conflict whose decisive moment is the cross and whose resolution is the new creation (Rev 19:11-16).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The massive armies &mdash; four hundred thousand on Judah&rsquo;s side, eight hundred thousand on Israel&rsquo;s &mdash; create the context for what follows: the victory will come not from numerical advantage but from calling on YHWH. This pattern of smaller-or-equal force prevailing by divine aid recurs throughout the Deuteronomic and Chronicler&rsquo;s history and points forward to the ultimate reversal: the crucified king who conquers by apparent defeat.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Abijah standing on Mount Zemaraim to address the northern kingdom before battle enacts the prophetic-royal preaching pattern: the anointed king speaking covenant truth to those who have departed from it. As a type, this scene prefigures Christ&rsquo;s preaching mission: the Son of David calling Israel back to the covenant, speaking truth from a high place (the Sermon on the Mount; the mountain discourse in Matt 5&ndash;7).</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;Do you not know that the LORD God of Israel gave David and his sons the kingship over Israel forever through a <em>bĕrît melaḥ</em> &mdash; a covenant of salt?&rdquo; The covenant of salt (Num 18:19; Lev 2:13) designated a permanent, incorruptible, irrevocable agreement &mdash; salt prevents decay and thus signifies that which cannot be undone. As a type, the irrevocable Davidic covenant is the OT scaffold on which the eternal Sonship of Christ stands: &ldquo;He will reign over Jacob&rsquo;s house forever; his kingdom will never end&rdquo; (Luke 1:33). Paul draws the same line: the gifts and calling of God are irrevocable (Rom 11:29).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Jeroboam &ldquo;rose up and rebelled against his master&rdquo; &mdash; the language of insubordination against the LORD&rsquo;s anointed. In the Psalmic framework, the nations that &ldquo;rage against the LORD and against his anointed&rdquo; (Ps 2:2) represent precisely this pattern of rebellion. Jeroboam&rsquo;s rebellion against Solomon&rsquo;s dynasty is a historical instance of the anti-messianic opposition that will find its fullest expression in the crucifixion.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;Worthless troublemakers&rdquo; (<em>ʾănaším rêqîm bĕnê-bĕliyyaʿal</em>) who &ldquo;overpowered Rehoboam when he was young and irresolute&rdquo; &mdash; the Chronicler notes the human weakness of the Davidic heir at that moment. Yet the line survived. This is the pattern of the messianic seed preserved through human frailty: the Davidic promise is not contingent on the strength of each individual heir but on YHWH&rsquo;s unconditional commitment (2 Sam 7:15-16).</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;Now you plan to oppose the kingdom of the LORD, held by David&rsquo;s descendants&rdquo; &mdash; <em>mamleket YHWH bĕyad bĕnê dāwîd</em>. The Chronicler explicitly identifies the Davidic dynasty with YHWH&rsquo;s own kingdom. Jeroboam&rsquo;s golden calves are named as the instruments of opposition to this. The calves echo the Sinai apostasy (Exod 32) &mdash; the prototype of Israel rejecting YHWH and fashioning a substitute. In the NT framework, opposition to Christ&rsquo;s kingdom takes the form of substitute ultimacies: the golden calf principle at every level of human existence.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;Have you not expelled the LORD&rsquo;s priests &mdash; the sons of Aaron and the Levites?&rdquo; The illegitimate priesthood of the northern kingdom is set against the Aaronic line. As a type, the question of legitimate priesthood runs through to Hebrews: Christ is the true high priest (Heb 4:14-5:10), not because he descends from Aaron but because he fulfills what Aaron only foreshadowed &mdash; the once-for-all, indestructible priestly ministry (Heb 7:15-17).</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;But we have the LORD as our God, and we have not abandoned him. The sons of Aaron serve as priests.&rdquo; Abijah&rsquo;s contrast &mdash; the northern cult versus the proper Levitical service &mdash; is more than liturgical: it is covenantal. The proper service points to Christ as the one true mediator (1 Tim 2:5) whose sacrifice the Levitical system only shadows. The burnt offerings morning and evening (v11) are the continuous expression of Israel&rsquo;s need for atoning mediation, fulfilled once for all at the cross (Heb 10:12).</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;Morning and evening they present burnt offerings and fragrant incense to the LORD, arrange the showbread on the pure table, and light the golden lampstand every evening.&rdquo; The tabernacle/temple liturgical rhythm &mdash; morning and evening sacrifice, incense, showbread, lampstand &mdash; is the continuous shadow pointing to Christ&rsquo;s perpetual intercession (Heb 7:25), his body as the bread of life (John 6:35), and his life as the light of the world (John 8:12). The shadow is preserved by Judah&rsquo;s faithfulness here.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;God is with us at our head, his priests are here with trumpets to sound the call against you.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;God is with us&rdquo; is the Emmanuel declaration in military context. It anticipates the virgin birth announcement: &ldquo;They shall call his name Emmanuel (which means, God with us)&rdquo; (Matt 1:23; Isa 7:14). The trumpets of the priests signaling divine aid point forward to the eschatological trumpets of Revelation (Rev 8-11) that announce God&rsquo;s final victory over his enemies.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Jeroboam&rsquo;s tactical ambush &mdash; troops in front, ambush behind &mdash; corresponds to the surrounded-on-all-sides position in which Israel often finds herself in the OT. This spatial encirclement is the situation of the covenant people in the world: opposed from every direction. The response in vv14-15 is the paradigm answer.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;They cried out to the LORD, and the priests blew their trumpets.&rdquo; The cry to YHWH in extremity is the Psalmic paradigm (Ps 18:6; 22:1-5; 34:6): calling on the LORD in distress, and the LORD hearing. The priestly trumpet blast invokes the divine warrior tradition of Numbers 10:9: &ldquo;When you go to war in your land against an adversary who oppresses you, you shall sound an alarm with the trumpets, that you may be remembered before the LORD your God, and you shall be saved from your enemies.&rdquo; Both elements point to Christ: his intercession as High Priest (the priestly action) and his response to the cry of faith (Heb 5:7).</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Judah raised a battle cry. As they shouted, God struck Jeroboam and all Israel down before Abijah and Judah.&rdquo; The divine act of routing the enemy at the moment of the covenant people&rsquo;s cry is the Holy War pattern that the NT reinterprets eschatologically: at the parousia, Christ will strike down his enemies with the sword of his mouth (Rev 19:15). The battle cry of faith is answered by divine action &mdash; not military superiority but the God who intervenes.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;God gave them into Judah&rsquo;s power.&rdquo; The passive construction &mdash; YHWH as the one who delivers enemies &mdash; is the Holy War formula throughout Judges and Samuel. As a theme, the sovereignty of God over the outcome of conflict is the constant undergirding of the Davidic narrative, pointing forward to Christ&rsquo;s resurrection as the ultimate divine act of vindication against all opposition.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The devastating defeat of Israel &mdash; five hundred thousand chosen men fallen &mdash; may be a hyperbolic round number, but the Chronicler&rsquo;s theological point is the totality of divine retribution on the rebellion against the Davidic covenant. As a theme, the absolute defeat of anti-messianic opposition anticipates Christ&rsquo;s eschatological victory: &ldquo;He must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet&rdquo; (1 Cor 15:25).</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;Israel was humbled at that time, and Judah prevailed because they relied on (<em>šāʿan</em> &mdash; leaned on) the LORD, the God of their ancestors.&rdquo; The verb <em>šāʿan</em> (H8172 &mdash; lean, rely on, trust) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s faith-word: the act of resting one&rsquo;s weight on YHWH rather than on human resources. The NT equivalent is faith (<em>pistis</em>) &mdash; the trust that leans on Christ&rsquo;s finished work rather than on the strength of flesh. Judah&rsquo;s prevailing &ldquo;because they relied on YHWH&rdquo; is the OT instance of justification by faith: the outcome is determined by trust, not by military strength.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Abijah&rsquo;s capture of Bethel &mdash; the northern site of Jeroboam&rsquo;s golden calf (1 Kgs 12:29) &mdash; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s signal that the rebellion against the Davidic covenant has suffered territorial reversal at its very center. Bethel (&ldquo;house of God&rdquo;) had been desecrated by idolatry; its capture by the faithful Davidic king is a shadow of Christ reclaiming what was lost through sin.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;Jeroboam never recovered his strength during Abijah&rsquo;s lifetime. The LORD struck him, and he died.&rdquo; The anti-Davidic ruler is struck down by YHWH &mdash; the same divine retribution the Chronicler notes for Herod (Acts 12:23 in the NT picks up this exact pattern: the king who blasphemes is struck down by an angel). Every ruler who opposes the LORD&rsquo;s anointed participates in a pattern that will find final fulfillment at the parousia.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Abijah&rsquo;s personal prosperity &mdash; fourteen wives, twenty-two sons, sixteen daughters &mdash; is the formulaic record of blessing. As a theme, the fruitfulness of the Davidic dynasty is part of the covenant blessing that points forward to Christ&rsquo;s &ldquo;offspring&rdquo; (Isa 53:10) &mdash; the innumerable family of God constituted through his sacrificial death.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The reference to &ldquo;the chronicle of the prophet Iddo&rdquo; closes Abijah&rsquo;s reign. The Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent appeal to prophetic sources signals that the Davidic history is interpreted through the prophetic lens &mdash; the prophets are the interpreters of the covenant. This prophetic-historical synthesis finds its ultimate expression in Christ, who is both the fulfillment of the prophetic word and the final Son of David about whom all prophecy speaks (Luke 24:44).</p>"
  },
  "14": {
    "1": "<p>&ldquo;The land was at peace and quiet for ten years&rdquo; under Asa. The word <em>šāqaṭ</em> (quiet, undisturbed) echoes the Deuteronomic rest-promise: YHWH gives rest to those who follow him. As a theme, the peace given to the faithful Davidic king anticipates the messianic peace &mdash; the <em>šālôm</em> that Isaiah 9:6-7 attributes to the Prince of Peace, whose government and peace shall have no end.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;Asa did what was good and right in the sight of the LORD his God.&rdquo; The double evaluation (<em>tôḇ wĕhayāšār</em> &mdash; good and upright) is reserved for the faithful kings in the Chronicler&rsquo;s evaluative system. As a revelation of God, what YHWH calls &ldquo;good and right&rdquo; is the standard that Christ perfectly embodies &mdash; not as one evaluated against it but as the one who is himself the standard (John 14:6: &ldquo;I am the way, the truth, and the life&rdquo;).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The removal of foreign altars and high places, smashing of sacred pillars, cutting down of Asherah poles &mdash; Asa&rsquo;s physical dismantling of the competing cult structures is the covenantal prerequisite for YHWH&rsquo;s dwelling with his people. As a type, this purification pattern points to Christ&rsquo;s temple cleansing (John 2:13-17; Matt 21:12-13) and ultimately to the new creation where nothing unclean enters (Rev 21:27).</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;He commanded the people of Judah to seek (<em>dāraš</em>) the LORD, the God of their ancestors, and to observe the law and commandment.&rdquo; The command to seek YHWH is the Chronicler&rsquo;s central theological imperative. As a theme, the seeking of God that the Chronicler diagnoses across the Davidic kings is what Jesus describes as the one thing necessary: &ldquo;Seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness&rdquo; (Matt 6:33). Seeking God means seeking Christ, who is &ldquo;the way&rdquo; to the Father (John 14:6).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Asa removes high places and incense altars &ldquo;from every town in Judah,&rdquo; and &ldquo;the kingdom was at peace under him.&rdquo; The connection &mdash; cultic reform produces social peace &mdash; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s retribution principle: faithfulness to YHWH brings <em>šālôm</em>. As a theme, the peace that follows the removal of idolatry anticipates the peace that follows the removal of sin through Christ&rsquo;s atonement: &ldquo;We have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ&rdquo; (Rom 5:1).</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;Because the LORD gave him rest and no war came against him&rdquo; &mdash; the causal connection between divine gift and human rest is explicit. This Deuteronomic rest-theology runs through the OT: rest in the land is YHWH&rsquo;s gift to the faithful (Deut 12:10; Josh 21:44). The NT develops this into the eschatological rest in Christ (Heb 4:9-11): &ldquo;There remains a Sabbath rest for the people of God.&rdquo; Asa&rsquo;s years of peace are a temporal instance of the eternal rest Christ provides.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;The land is still ours because we sought the LORD our God&rdquo; (<em>kî dāraštānû YHWH ʾĕlōhênû</em>) &mdash; the seeking-land connection makes explicit what the Chronicler implies throughout: the land inheritance is sustained by seeking YHWH, not by military power. As a theme, the inheritance-through-seeking principle points to Christ, in whom &ldquo;we have obtained an inheritance&rdquo; (Eph 1:11) &mdash; not through strength but through union with the one who is himself sought and found.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Asa&rsquo;s military census &mdash; three hundred thousand spear-and-shield men from Judah, two hundred eighty thousand archers from Benjamin &mdash; establishes the human military baseline before the Zerah encounter. The contrast that follows (vv9-11) makes the point: even this significant force is inadequate against &ldquo;a million men&rdquo; without YHWH&rsquo;s help. As a revelation of God, the pattern establishes that human military capacity is always insufficient against the forces that oppose the covenant people &mdash; the resource that matters is divine.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Zerah the Cushite advancing with &ldquo;a million men and three hundred chariots&rdquo; represents an overwhelming military threat &mdash; a force Judah cannot match on any human calculus. This is the structural setup for the paradigmatic prayer of v11: when the odds are impossible, the response of faith is direct appeal to YHWH. As a theme, the overwhelming-force scenario that precedes the prayer of faith recurs throughout the OT (the Red Sea, Gideon&rsquo;s three hundred, Elisha surrounded by Arameans) and anticipates the crucifixion: the moment of total apparent defeat from which God works his greatest victory.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Valley of Zephathah near Mareshah is the site of the confrontation &mdash; a location in the Shephelah, the foothills between Judah&rsquo;s highlands and the coastal plain. The geographic note grounds the miraculous in historical specificity. This is the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent method: the divine acts of deliverance are not mythological abstractions but events located in real places, which is how Christ&rsquo;s incarnation and resurrection work &mdash; located in a specific place, a specific time, a specific tomb.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;LORD, only you can help the powerless against the mighty. Help us, LORD our God, for we rely on you, and in your name we have come against this vast multitude. LORD, you are our God; do not let anyone prevail against you.&rdquo; Asa&rsquo;s prayer is one of the great paradigmatic prayers of faith in the OT: (1) acknowledgment of human powerlessness, (2) sole reliance on YHWH (<em>ʿālêkā nišʿānnû</em> &mdash; on you we lean), (3) appeal to the divine name, (4) reframing the battle as YHWH&rsquo;s own contest. The final phrase &mdash; &ldquo;do not let anyone prevail against you&rdquo; &mdash; transfers the defense from Judah&rsquo;s own honor to YHWH&rsquo;s. This is the faith-posture that the NT calls upon in the name of Christ: &ldquo;I can do all things through Christ who strengthens me&rdquo; (Phil 4:13).</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD struck down the Cushites before Asa and Judah, and they fled.&rdquo; The divine warrior acts in response to faith. As a type, this divine rout of the overwhelming enemy anticipates Christ&rsquo;s resurrection defeat of death and sin: what appeared to be the stronger force (death, the curse, the law&rsquo;s accusation) is struck down by divine action in response to the Son&rsquo;s own cry of trust (Heb 5:7; Ps 22).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Asa&rsquo;s forces pursue the routed Cushites all the way to Gerar &mdash; &ldquo;they were crushed before the LORD and before his army.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;before the LORD and before his army&rdquo; (<em>lipnê YHWH wĕlipnê maḥănēhû</em>) reveals the theological reality: Asa&rsquo;s army is YHWH&rsquo;s army. As a shadow, the militarized covenant people enacting divine judgment anticipates the armies of heaven following the rider on the white horse (Rev 19:14) &mdash; the final expression of the divine warrior theme.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;The terror of the LORD (<em>paḥad YHWH</em>) had fallen on those towns.&rdquo; Divine terror falling on surrounding nations is the Holy War motif of the conquest tradition (Exod 15:16; Josh 2:9). As a theme, the nations&rsquo; fear before YHWH&rsquo;s advancing covenant people anticipates the eschatological submission of all nations to Christ: &ldquo;Every knee shall bow&rdquo; (Phil 2:10), whether in willing worship or unwilling defeat.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The plunder of livestock and the return to Jerusalem closes the Zerah episode. The return to Jerusalem &mdash; the city of the Davidic king and the temple &mdash; is the natural terminus of the Holy War: the plunder is brought back to the center of YHWH&rsquo;s covenant presence. This centralization of blessing in Jerusalem is the shadow of the eschatological city where the kings of the earth bring their glory and honor (Rev 21:26).</p>"
  },
  "15": {
    "1": "<p>&ldquo;The Spirit of God came upon Azariah son of Oded.&rdquo; The Spirit&rsquo;s coming upon a prophet in a unique commissioning for a specific prophetic word is the OT pattern of prophetic inspiration (Num 11:25; 1 Sam 19:20; 2 Chr 20:14). As a type, the Spirit coming upon individual prophets anticipates the Pentecostal outpouring when the Spirit comes upon all flesh (Acts 2:17-18; Joel 2:28-29). Azariah is empowered to deliver a word that will determine the trajectory of Asa&rsquo;s reign.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD is with you as long as you are with him. Seek him (<em>diršûhû</em>) and he will be found by you; but if you abandon him, he will abandon you.&rdquo; This is the Chronicler&rsquo;s most compressed statement of the covenant condition &mdash; and one of the closest OT anticipations of the seeking-finding promise Jesus himself gives: &ldquo;Ask and it will be given to you; seek and you will find; knock and the door will be opened&rdquo; (Matt 7:7-8; Luke 11:9-10). Both texts use the seeking-finding structure with the implied promise: the one sought by faith will be found. In the NT, the one to be found is Christ himself (John 1:41: &ldquo;We have found the Messiah&rdquo;).</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;For many years Israel had no true God, no teaching priest, and no law.&rdquo; The threefold absence &mdash; God, priest, law &mdash; describes Israel in its lowest condition: abandoned to the consequences of apostasy. As a theme, this triple absence is exactly what Christ supplies: he is the Way to God (the true God found), the great High Priest (Heb 4:14), and the fulfillment of the law (Matt 5:17). The desolate condition described in v3 is the condition the new covenant addresses.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;But when in their distress they turned to the LORD, the God of Israel, and sought him, he let them find him.&rdquo; The seeking-finding pattern in history: YHWH allows himself to be found by those who genuinely seek him in their distress. As a theme, this describes the entire arc of OT seeking that culminates in Christ&rsquo;s incarnation: God lets himself be found &mdash; he enters the world as the one to be found. The incarnation is God&rsquo;s ultimate act of making himself findable (John 1:14; Heb 1:1-2).</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;In those times it was dangerous to travel, for great turmoil troubled everyone in every land.&rdquo; The social chaos of the period without seeking God is part of the retribution pattern: the absence of covenant faithfulness produces societal disorder. As a theme, the violence and insecurity that follow from abandoning God is what the messianic peace reverses: the Prince of Peace (Isa 9:6) brings not merely political stability but the comprehensive <em>šālôm</em> that the presence of God creates.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;Nation fought nation and city attacked city, for God sent every kind of adversity to trouble them.&rdquo; Divine sovereign use of international conflict as an instrument of covenantal discipline is the prophetic theology applied to history. Isaiah&rsquo;s portrayal of YHWH using Assyria as &ldquo;the rod of my anger&rdquo; (Isa 10:5) is the paradigm. As a revelation of God, this verse establishes that history&rsquo;s conflicts are not beyond divine governance &mdash; a claim that the NT extends: Christ&rsquo;s authority extends to &ldquo;all authority in heaven and on earth&rdquo; (Matt 28:18).</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;But as for you, be strong, and do not give up, for your work will be rewarded.&rdquo; Azariah&rsquo;s exhortation combines the Deuteronomic commissioning formula (&ldquo;be strong,&rdquo; <em>ḥizqû</em>) with the promise of covenantal reward. As a theme, the promise that faithful work will be rewarded runs through the NT into eschatology: &ldquo;Each one will receive his own reward according to his own labor&rdquo; (1 Cor 3:8); &ldquo;your labor in the Lord is not in vain&rdquo; (1 Cor 15:58). The reward-promise is grounded in Christ&rsquo;s faithfulness as the foundation on which the covenant people build.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Asa responds to the prophecy by removing &ldquo;the detestable idols from the whole land of Judah and Benjamin&rdquo; and renewing &ldquo;the altar of the LORD that was in front of the portico of the LORD&rsquo;s temple.&rdquo; The restoration of the altar is the act of covenant re-centering: sacrifice returns to its proper place. As a type, the altar is the locus of atonement &mdash; the place where the offense of sin against a holy God is addressed through blood. Every renewed altar in the OT is a shadow of the one sacrifice that Christ offers &ldquo;once for all&rdquo; (Heb 10:10), making all further atoning altars unnecessary.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The gathering of the assembly from both Judah and Benjamin and from &ldquo;settlers from Ephraim, Manasseh, and Simeon who had come to live with them&rdquo; is significant: the covenant renewal draws from both north and south. This pan-Israelite gathering &mdash; transcending the political division &mdash; anticipates the eschatological gathering of all Israel (Ezek 37:15-28; Rom 11:26). As a shadow, it prefigures the one people of God constituted in Christ from both Jew and Gentile (Eph 2:14-16).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The assembly in Jerusalem &ldquo;in the third month of the fifteenth year of Asa&rsquo;s reign&rdquo; &mdash; the third month corresponds to Pentecost (Shavuot), the feast of weeks. The covenant renewal assembly at Pentecost connects to the giving of the law at Sinai (Exod 19:1) and ultimately to the NT Pentecost when the Spirit is poured out and the new covenant community is constituted (Acts 2). The timing is not explicitly noted by the Chronicler but is inherent in the third-month reference.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The sacrifice of seven hundred cattle and seven thousand sheep from the plunder on that day is the festive sacrifice that accompanies covenant renewal &mdash; a massive offering of thanksgiving and consecration. As a type, the blood of sacrificial animals at covenant ceremonies is the shadow of the covenant established through Christ&rsquo;s blood (Matt 26:28; Heb 9:18-22): &ldquo;Without the shedding of blood there is no forgiveness of sins&rdquo; (Heb 9:22).</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;They entered into a covenant to seek the LORD, the God of their ancestors, with all their heart and soul.&rdquo; The seeking-covenant formula uses the Shema-love vocabulary of Deuteronomy 6:5 (&ldquo;with all your heart and with all your soul&rdquo;). As a type, this covenant to seek with all heart and soul is precisely the new covenant promise fulfilled in Christ: YHWH promises to give his people the heart that seeks him (Jer 31:33; Ezek 36:26; Deut 30:6). The covenant made here in 2 Chr 15:12 is the human pledge; the new covenant in Christ is the divine provision that makes the human pledge possible.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;Anyone who refused to seek the LORD was to be put to death.&rdquo; The death penalty for covenant refusal reflects the totalizing character of the Sinai covenant: there is no neutral position before YHWH. As a theme, the absolute claim of covenant loyalty &mdash; you are either with YHWH or against him &mdash; is what Jesus intensifies: &ldquo;Whoever is not with me is against me&rdquo; (Matt 12:30). The death penalty for rejecting YHWH is the OT expression of what the NT presents as the spiritual reality of spiritual death for those who refuse Christ (John 3:36).</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;They swore their oath to the LORD with a loud voice, with shouting, and with trumpets and horns.&rdquo; The public, embodied, vocal covenant oath &mdash; with the full sensory apparatus of trumpets, shouting, and proclamation &mdash; is the corporate covenant-making act. As a theme, this vocal public confession anticipates the NT&rsquo;s confession (<em>homologia</em>) of Christ: &ldquo;If you confess with your mouth &lsquo;Jesus is Lord&rsquo; and believe in your heart&rdquo; (Rom 10:9). The loud oath of covenant loyalty to YHWH is the OT form of what confession of Christ is in the new covenant.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;All Judah rejoiced over the oath, for they swore it wholeheartedly, sought him eagerly, and he was found by them. The LORD gave them rest on every side.&rdquo; The threefold structure &mdash; wholehearted seeking &rarr; finding YHWH &rarr; rest given &mdash; is the complete covenant-blessing sequence. The seeking-finding-rest triad is the OT prototype of what Christ promises: &ldquo;Come to me&hellip; and I will give you rest&rdquo; (Matt 11:28-29). Hebrews 4 explicitly develops this rest-theology: the Sabbath rest promised to the faithful seeking people is realized in Christ.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Asa deposes even his grandmother Maacah from the position of queen mother because she had made a repulsive image of Asherah. The removal of the <em>gĕbîrâ</em> (queen mother) &mdash; a powerful court position in the ancient Near East &mdash; to preserve covenant purity demonstrates that family loyalty does not override covenant obligation. As a theme, this anticipates Jesus&rsquo;s own declaration: &ldquo;Whoever loves father or mother more than me is not worthy of me&rdquo; (Matt 10:37). Covenant with YHWH &mdash; and with Christ &mdash; demands the highest loyalty.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&ldquo;The high places were not eliminated from Israel. Yet Asa&rsquo;s heart remained fully devoted (<em>šālēm</em>) throughout his life.&rdquo; The apparent contradiction &mdash; incomplete reform, complete heart &mdash; is resolved by the Chronicler&rsquo;s theology: YHWH evaluates the heart&rsquo;s orientation, not merely the completeness of institutional reform. As a revelation of God, this verse establishes that YHWH sees the heart as the primary locus of faithfulness &mdash; the principle that Paul grounds in justification by faith rather than by legal completeness (Rom 4:3-5).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The dedicated gifts &mdash; silver, gold, and articles &mdash; brought into the house of God represent the king&rsquo;s consecration of his resources to YHWH&rsquo;s service. As a theme, the dedication of wealth to the temple is the OT form of what Paul calls &ldquo;presenting your bodies as a living sacrifice, holy and pleasing to God&rdquo; (Rom 12:1): the whole person and all resources consecrated to divine service.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;There was no war until the thirty-fifth year of Asa&rsquo;s reign.&rdquo; The long peace that followed the covenant renewal (cf. the long peace under Solomon) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent sign of covenant blessing. As a theme, the extended peace that follows faithfulness is the temporal shadow of the eternal peace Christ establishes &mdash; the peace &ldquo;that surpasses all understanding&rdquo; (Phil 4:7) and that the Prince of Peace will sustain with justice and righteousness forever (Isa 9:7).</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>Baasha&rsquo;s fortification of Ramah to block movement to and from Jerusalem is a political-military act aimed at cutting Judah off from its center. The attack on access to Jerusalem &mdash; the city of the Davidic king and the temple &mdash; is a recurrent pattern in the OT: those who oppose the covenant king attack the city of YHWH&rsquo;s presence. As a type, the besieged Jerusalem anticipates the opposition to Christ&rsquo;s own city and temple that culminates in the AD 70 destruction &mdash; and ultimately in the opposition to the heavenly Jerusalem that will finally be overcome (Rev 21:1-4).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Asa takes silver and gold from the temple and palace treasuries to pay Ben-hadad of Aram for military assistance against Baasha. This is the fateful departure: temple treasure deployed as political currency rather than covenant trust exercised in prayer. As a theme, this parallels the fundamental temptation to leverage God&rsquo;s resources (gifts, covenantal identity, even Scripture) for political advantage rather than trusting in divine provision alone &mdash; the temptation that Jesus refuses in the wilderness (Matt 4:1-11).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The treaty language &mdash; &ldquo;Let there be a treaty between you and me, as between our fathers&rdquo; &mdash; frames the arrangement as a horizontal covenant replacing the vertical covenant with YHWH. Asa makes a <em>bĕrît</em> with Aram rather than relying on his <em>bĕrît</em> with YHWH. As a theme, the substitution of human alliances for divine covenant is the prophetic critique running from Isaiah (Isa 30:1-5; 31:1-3) to Jeremiah (Jer 2:13: &ldquo;My people have committed two evils: they have forsaken me&hellip; and hewed out cisterns for themselves&rdquo;). Christ as the mediator of the new covenant is the answer to this substitution pattern.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Ben-hadad&rsquo;s attack on northern Israel succeeds &mdash; Asa&rsquo;s human strategy works in the short term. The apparent success of the faithless strategy is the trap: it &ldquo;works&rdquo; by the world&rsquo;s calculus but costs the relationship with YHWH that is the actual basis of security. As a theme, the short-term success of pragmatic compromise at the cost of covenant integrity is what Hanani&rsquo;s prophecy (vv7-9) names as the real loss.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Baasha withdraws from Ramah when his northern cities are threatened &mdash; Asa&rsquo;s diplomatic strategy achieves its immediate military objective. The verse stands as the record of what was gained by the compromise: a relief from immediate pressure. What was lost is named by the prophet in vv7-9: the opportunity for a greater victory and the trust relationship with YHWH that makes all victories possible.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Asa uses the materials from Ramah to build Geba and Mizpah &mdash; converting the threat into fortification. The practical competence of Asa&rsquo;s response is undeniable. The Chronicler records it without comment here, letting the prophetic indictment of v7-9 provide the theological evaluation. As a theme, human competence that displaces divine dependence is not always obviously disastrous in the short term &mdash; which is precisely what makes it dangerous.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;Because you relied on (<em>nišʿanta</em>) the king of Syria and not on the LORD your God, the army of the king of Syria has escaped you.&rdquo; Hanani the seer names the theological error: the same verb <em>šāʿan</em> (lean, rely on) used positively in 14:11 (Asa relying on YHWH against the Cushites) is now used negatively. Asa has transferred his leaning from YHWH to Aram. As a revelation of God, this verse establishes that where trust is placed determines outcome &mdash; a principle that Paul develops into the theology of faith: righteousness comes by trusting God, not by leaning on human resources (Rom 4:3-5; Gal 3:11).</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;Remember the Cushites and Libyans &mdash; weren&rsquo;t they a massive force? Yet because you relied on the LORD, he delivered them into your hand.&rdquo; Hanani rehearses the contrast: the Zerah victory (ch 14) was won precisely because Asa trusted YHWH. The past faithfulness that produced the greater victory is the standard against which the current faithlessness is measured. As a theme, the appeal to past experience of divine faithfulness as the ground for present trust is the pattern of Psalm 22:4-5 and of Paul&rsquo;s comfort theology (2 Cor 1:9-10): &ldquo;On him we have set our hope that he will continue to deliver us.&rdquo;</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;The eyes of the LORD range throughout the earth to strengthen those whose hearts are fully committed to him.&rdquo; (<em>ʿênê YHWH mĕšōṭĕṭôt bĕkol-hāʾāreṣ lĕhitḥazzēq ʿim-lĕḇāḇām šālēm ʾēlāyw</em>.) This is one of the great verses in Chronicles &mdash; the omniscient search of YHWH for hearts wholly devoted to him. As a theme, this divine scrutiny of the heart becomes in the NT the omniscience of Christ: the seven spirits (seven eyes) of the Lamb range through all the earth (Rev 5:6; Zech 4:10), and Christ knows the hearts of all the churches (Rev 2-3: &ldquo;I know your works&rdquo;). The search is not punitive but strengthening: YHWH actively empowers the heart that is his. The tragedy is that Asa&rsquo;s heart was <em>šālēm</em> (15:17) &mdash; but in this moment he chose otherwise.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Asa &ldquo;was furious with the seer and threw him in prison.&rdquo; The king&rsquo;s rage at the prophetic rebuke follows the pattern of every king in the OT who silences the messenger of divine judgment: Ahab imprisons Micaiah (1 Kgs 22:27), Jeremiah is thrown in a cistern (Jer 38:6), Zechariah son of Jehoiada is stoned (2 Chr 24:21). As a type, Asa&rsquo;s imprisonment of Hanani prefigures the systematic rejection of the prophets that Jesus names as the defining sin of Jerusalem (Matt 23:37) and that culminates in the killing of Christ himself, the final prophet (Heb 1:1-2).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The reference to &ldquo;the Book of the Kings of Judah and Israel&rdquo; as the source for Asa&rsquo;s complete record is the Chronicler&rsquo;s standard citation form. As a revelation of God, this historiographical note establishes that YHWH&rsquo;s acts in history are documented and remembered &mdash; a principle that Paul applies to the OT as a whole: &ldquo;Whatever was written in former days was written for our instruction&rdquo; (Rom 15:4). The history is not merely past but alive as instruction.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;In the thirty-ninth year of his reign, Asa developed a severe foot disease. Yet even in his illness he did not seek (<em>dāraš</em>) the LORD, but only the physicians.&rdquo; The fatal recurrence of the faithless pattern: the same failure to seek YHWH that characterized the Syrian alliance now governs Asa&rsquo;s response to illness. The contrast with Hezekiah (who prayed when ill, 2 Chr 32:24) is direct. As a theme, the refusal to seek YHWH in extremity is the paradigm of what the NT calls unbelief: the turn to human resources as the primary resort, with God as a secondary backup at best. The seeking-theology of the Chronicler culminates in Christ as the ultimate physician &mdash; the one who heals not just physical disease but the disease of sin (Mark 2:17).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Asa dies in the forty-first year of his reign. The Chronicler records the death as a historical fact without explicit theological comment &mdash; the accumulated evidence of vv7-12 speaks for itself. As a theme, the end of a reign that began so well (chs 14-15) and ended in compromise and refusal to seek YHWH stands as the warning that faithfulness must be sustained to the end. The NT&rsquo;s &ldquo;he who endures to the end will be saved&rdquo; (Matt 24:13) is the same principle.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Asa&rsquo;s honorable burial &mdash; in the tomb he had made for himself, with perfumes and spices, with a great fire of honor &mdash; suggests that the community&rsquo;s memory of Asa honored his earlier faithfulness. The Chronicler records the elaborate burial without editorial comment, allowing the contrast between the honored death and the failed final years to stand. As a theme, the burial with honor gestures toward resurrection hope &mdash; the body laid in the tomb matters because YHWH is the God who raises the dead (Dan 12:2; John 5:28-29).</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>Jehoshaphat &ldquo;consolidated his position against Israel&rdquo; &mdash; the new king immediately secures the frontier with the northern kingdom. As a theme, the faithful Davidic king must consistently hold his ground against the rival Israelite alternative to the Davidic covenant. As a shadow of Christ, this frontier-securing points to the kingdom that cannot be shaken (Heb 12:28): the Son of David who holds his position against every opposition.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The military presence in Judah&rsquo;s cities and in the Ephraimite cities that Asa had captured establishes Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s administrative control. The Chronicler records the practical governance of the faithful king with approval: faithful kingship involves responsible administration of the gifts and territory YHWH has given. As a theme, the stewardship of resources and territory under divine authority anticipates the parable of the talents (Matt 25:14-30): faithful governance of what is entrusted is the expected response to divine blessing.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD was with Jehoshaphat because he followed the earlier example of his ancestor David.&rdquo; The Davidic model &mdash; the prototype against which each king is measured &mdash; is here explicitly the &ldquo;earlier&rdquo; David, not the compromised David of his later years. The Chronicler distinguishes the faithful from the unfaithful phases of David&rsquo;s life as the standard. As a type, the perfect Davidic model that no actual son of David fully achieves points to the one who will embody it completely &mdash; the Son of David who is also the Son of God (Matt 1:1; Rom 1:3-4).</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;He sought the God of his father (<em>wayyiḏrōš lēʾlōhê ʾāḇîw</em>) and followed his commands, not the practices of Israel.&rdquo; Seeking God and following his commands are linked as the two elements of covenant faithfulness. As a theme, this seeking-obedience pairing is what Jesus describes as the kingdom life: &ldquo;Seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness&rdquo; (Matt 6:33). The &ldquo;practices of Israel&rdquo; (the northern kingdom&rsquo;s syncretism) represent the alternative to seeking &mdash; the pragmatic accommodation to surrounding culture that the prophets consistently condemn.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD therefore established his rule firmly. All Judah brought him tribute, and he had great riches and honor.&rdquo; The causal chain &mdash; seeking YHWH &rarr; divine establishment of the kingdom &rarr; wealth and honor from the nations &mdash; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s retribution principle for Jehoshaphat. As a theme, the nations bringing tribute to the faithful Davidic king is the OT form of the eschatological tribute to Christ: &ldquo;the kings of the earth will bring their splendor into&rdquo; the new Jerusalem (Rev 21:24).</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;His heart was devoted to the LORD&rsquo;s ways. He also removed the high places and Asherah poles from Judah.&rdquo; The heart-devotion preceding institutional reform is the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent sequence: the inner orientation of the heart governs the outer reform of the cult. As a revelation of God, this verse confirms the Deuteronomic priority of the heart (Deut 6:5; 30:6): true covenant faithfulness begins with the heart and works outward. This is the new covenant promise in Ezekiel 36:26 and Jeremiah 31:33: YHWH will give the heart that Jehoshaphat already has.</p>",
    "7": "<p>In his third year, Jehoshaphat sends officials to teach throughout the cities of Judah. The teaching mission begins with named royal officials &mdash; the administrative class &mdash; as the primary teachers, supplemented by Levites and priests (v8). As a type, the royal sending of teachers to every city of Judah anticipates the Great Commission (Matt 28:19-20): Christ the king sends his disciples to teach all nations. The parallel is structural: the king&rsquo;s sending, the content (law/word of God), the geographic scope (all cities/all nations).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Levites and priests accompany the officials in the teaching mission &mdash; &ldquo;With them he sent Levites&rdquo; and also priests Elishama and Jehoram. The combination of civil officials, Levites, and priests mirrors the comprehensive institutional deployment of the word. As a theme, the Levitical teaching role in the Second Temple period sustains the teaching tradition that will culminate in the scribal and synagogue institutions of Jesus&rsquo;s day &mdash; the institutions through which he himself taught (Luke 4:16-21).</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;They taught throughout Judah, taking with them the Book of the Law of the LORD (<em>sēper tôrat YHWH</em>). They traveled to every town in Judah and taught the people.&rdquo; The dissemination of the Torah to every town in Judah &mdash; the word of God carried by royal envoys to every community &mdash; is the OT version of the Word going out to all. As a direct type of the Great Commission, this verse prefigures the apostolic mission: the risen King sends his messengers with his word to every town (Acts 8:25; 13:49). The &ldquo;Book of the Law&rdquo; they carry becomes, in the new covenant, the gospel &mdash; the good news of the King himself.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;The terror of the LORD fell on all the kingdoms of the lands surrounding Judah, so that they did not make war against Jehoshaphat.&rdquo; The <em>paḥad YHWH</em> (terror of YHWH) on surrounding nations echoes the conquest tradition (Exod 15:16; Josh 2:9-11) and the Asa narrative (14:14). As a theme, the nations standing in awe before YHWH&rsquo;s anointed king and making peace rather than war anticipates the eschatological submission of nations to Christ: &ldquo;All kings shall fall down before him; all nations shall serve him&rdquo; (Ps 72:11).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Philistines and Arabs bring tribute &mdash; silver and flocks &mdash; to Jehoshaphat. As a theme, this Gentile tribute to the Davidic king is the recurring OT form of what the prophets project onto the messianic future: &ldquo;Nations shall come to your light, and kings to the brightness of your dawn&rdquo; (Isa 60:3). The movement of Gentiles bringing gifts to Jerusalem&rsquo;s king is precisely what Matthew sees in the Magi&rsquo;s visit to the infant Christ (Matt 2:1-12).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s growing power and building program &mdash; fortresses and supply cities throughout Judah &mdash; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s formula for covenant blessing materialized in governance. As a theme, the faithful king who builds up the kingdom through legitimate means (not through alliances with pagan powers, as Asa did in ch 16) embodies the stewardship principle that Christ expects of those who exercise authority in his name (Luke 19:17).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The large stores and mighty fighting men stationed in Jerusalem support the king&rsquo;s military capacity. The combination of supply infrastructure and military force in Jerusalem &mdash; the city of YHWH&rsquo;s presence &mdash; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s picture of a well-ordered kingdom. As a shadow, this provision for the king&rsquo;s city anticipates the provision of the new Jerusalem, sustained not by human military force but by the glory of God himself (Rev 21:23-25).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The military muster by ancestral divisions begins with Adnah the commander with three hundred thousand from Judah. The genealogical-military organization reflects the tribal structure established in Numbers 1-2 for the wilderness camp: each tribe has its appointed place in the covenant army. As a theme, the ordered covenant army of Judah is a shadow of the ordered people of God &mdash; the twelve tribes of Israel reappearing in Revelation 7:4-8 as the sealed servants of God from all the tribes.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Jehohanan the commander with two hundred eighty thousand continues the muster. As a theme, the enumeration of fighting men by name and division is part of the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent interest in the organized, properly-structured covenant community. This ordered structure reflects the character of God who &ldquo;is not a God of disorder but of peace&rdquo; (1 Cor 14:33).</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;Amasiah son of Zichri, who had volunteered for the LORD&rsquo;s service.&rdquo; The designation <em>hmitnaḏḏēḇ laYHWH</em> &mdash; &ldquo;who had volunteered himself to YHWH&rdquo; &mdash; is distinctive: this officer is noted not just for his fighting capacity but for his willing dedication. As a theme, voluntary consecration to YHWH&rsquo;s service &mdash; not conscription but freely offered devotion &mdash; is the spirit of the new covenant response to grace: &ldquo;I urge you, brothers, in view of God&rsquo;s mercy, to offer your bodies as a living sacrifice&rdquo; (Rom 12:1). Amasiah embodies this spirit.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Eliada the mighty warrior from Benjamin with two hundred thousand archers. The Benjaminite contingent in Judah&rsquo;s army reflects the incorporation of the smaller southern tribe into Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s unified force. As a theme, the gathering of both Judah and Benjamin into the Davidic army is part of the partial restoration of the divided kingdom &mdash; a foretaste of the full reunion of all Israel under the eschatological Davidic king (Ezek 37:19-22).</p>",
    "18": "<p>Jehozabad with a hundred and eighty thousand equipped for war completes the Benjamin muster. The total force approaches one million &mdash; a hyperbolic number that signals the fullness of blessing and military capacity granted to the faithful king. As a theme, the abundance of the covenant blessing given to the seeking king overflows all human expectation &mdash; pointing to the God &ldquo;who is able to do far more abundantly than all that we ask or think&rdquo; (Eph 3:20).</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;These served the king, in addition to those he had stationed in the fortified cities throughout Judah.&rdquo; The closing summary reveals that the muster of vv14-18 is only the central army; the regional garrisons add further capacity. As a revelation of God, the comprehensive military provision for the faithful king &mdash; resources exceeding what is listed &mdash; reflects the inexhaustible provision of YHWH for those who seek him. This is the pattern of grace that Paul describes: &ldquo;My God will meet all your needs according to the riches of his glory in Christ Jesus&rdquo; (Phil 4:19).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', '2chronicles')
    merge_comm(c, CHRON2)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '2chronicles', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in CHRON2.values())
    print(f'2chronicles mkt-christ: wrote {count} verses for ch 13-17')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
